Singapore Stocks Poised for Biggest Two-Day Decline Since 2008

-- B y   L y n n   T h o m a s s o n
-- 
2011-08-08T06:34:04Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-08/singapore-stocks-poised-for-biggest-two-day-decline-since-2008.html
Singapore ’s  Straits Times Index (FSSTI) 
dropped 4 percent to 2,873.87 as of 2:31 p.m. local time and is
headed for the biggest two-day drop since October 2008. The
gauge fell 3.6 percent on Aug. 5 amid concern the global economy
is slowing and the U.S. may enter a recession.  The index was valued at 13.7 times estimated profit on Aug.
5, compared with about 15.6 times at the end of 2010, according
to data compiled by Bloomberg.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Keppel Corp. (KEP SP) tumbled 4.7 percent to S$9.82. Keppel
FELS Ltd. received an order from Transocean Offshore Deepwater
Holdings Ltd. to build a jackup drilling rig for $195 million,
Keppel Corp. said in an e-mailed statement.  Tiger Airways Holdings Ltd. (TGR)   slumped 4.3 percent to
S$1.015. The airline was cut to “underperform” from “trading
sell” at CIMB by equity analyst Raymond Yap.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Lynn Thomasson in  Hong Kong  at 
 lthomasson@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at 
 ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 